<paragraph blockId="89.[151,1437,476,611]" pageId="89" pageNumber="90">
A monotypic genus recently discovered in Ecuador. See De Marmels (2001a) for identification. Adults are mostly brown and tan with the tips of the abdomen grayish white (
<figureCitation box="[822,907,549,575]" captionStart="FIGURE 48" captionStartId="89.[151,250,1307,1332]" captionTargetBox="[302,1286,633,1288]" captionTargetId="figure@89.[302,1286,633,1288]" captionTargetPageId="89" captionText="FIGURE 48. Megapodagrion megalopus ♂, PERU: Loreto Department, Tamshiyacu, Tahuayo National Park; 6 viii 2009; photo T. Faasen." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3339980/files/figure.png" pageId="89" pageNumber="90">Fig. 48</figureCitation>
); they perch with their wings out. The nymphs and their habitat are apparently unknown.
</paragraph>
